### 3.2 add-new-page.md — new "Convention" note

**File:** `docs/add-new-page.md`

**Current structure (per basher, 138 lines):** 5-step process + Paper & Ink compliance checklist.

**Augmentation:** add a new sub-section under "Paper & Ink compliance" or create a new section "Border & Utility Conventions":

**Content (insert as new sub-section, e.g. after the compliance checklist):**

```markdown
## Border & Utility Conventions

### When to use `hairline` vs `pi-dashed-panel` vs `pi-corner-marks`

| Pattern | Use when | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `hairline` (1px solid `var(--color-rule)`) | Default border for all structural panels, cards, tables, dividers. | `<div class="hairline bg-paper p-stack-lg">` |
| `pi-dashed-panel` (1px dashed `var(--color-rule)`) | Empty states, draft cards, "no data" placeholders. | `<div class="pi-dashed-panel p-stack-lg text-center">` |
| `pi-corner-marks` (8px L-shapes) | Empty states, structural cards, showcase panels. Opt-in for visual emphasis. | `<div class="pi-corner-marks hairline p-stack-lg">` |

**Rule of thumb:** start with `hairline` for ALL structural surfaces. Add `pi-corner-marks` only for empty states or showcase panels. Add `pi-dashed-panel` only for near-empty/draft surfaces. Never combine `pi-dashed-panel` with solid content fills (use it for containers that are intentionally empty or draft).

### When to use `pi-tech-label`

`pi-tech-label` is for engineering metadata (REF numbers, IDs, system versions) in corners of structural panels. It's NOT for body text, table headers, or button labels. For those, use the existing `eyebrow` class.

**See:** `docs/paper-and-ink.md` § "Pi-* Architectural Utilities", `/kit/foundations` Section V.
```

**Acceptance:**
- New "Border & Utility Conventions" section is added.
- Table clearly distinguishes `hairline` vs `pi-dashed-panel` vs `pi-corner-marks`.
- Rule of thumb is actionable.

